Package ohos.bluetooth

Class DataListenSocket

  • java.lang.Object
    • ohos.bluetooth.DataListenSocket

  • public class DataListenSocket
extends Object
    Listens to Bluetooth data transmission.

    This class provides four methods for creating a Bluetooth socket:

    • dataListenInsecureRfcomm(java.lang.String,java.util.UUID): creates an insecure RFCOMM Bluetooth server listening socket based on service records.
    • dataListenRfcomm(java.lang.String,java.util.UUID): creates a secure RFCOMM Bluetooth server listening socket based on service records.
    • buildInsecureRfcommDataSocket(ohos.bluetooth.BluetoothRemoteDevice,java.util.UUID):Creates an insecure RFCOMM Bluetooth client socket based on the service record.
    • buildRfcommDataSocket(ohos.bluetooth.BluetoothRemoteDevice,java.util.UUID):Creates an secure RFCOMM Bluetooth client socket based on the service record.
    Since:
    7

    • Method Detail

      • dataListenInsecureRfcomm

        public SppServerSocket dataListenInsecureRfcomm​(String name,
                                                UUID uuid)
                                         throws IOException
        Creates an insecure RFCOMM Bluetooth server listening socket based on the service record.

        This connection mode does not require link key authentication and may encounter man-in-the-middle attacks. For Bluetooth 2.1 devices, the link will be forcibly encrypted. For devices using earlier Bluetooth versions, the link will not be encrypted. If you need an encrypted communication channel, use dataListenRfcomm(java.lang.String, java.util.UUID).

        Use SppServerSocket#accept to retrieve incoming connections from devices.

        The system will assign an unused RFCOMM channel.

        The system registers a Service Discovery Protocol (SDP) record with the local SDP server, records the service name, and automatically assigns a channel. Remote Bluetooth devices can use the same UUID to query the SDP server and identify the channel to connect to. This SDP record will be removed if the socket is disabled or the application exits unexpectedly.

        Parameters:
        name - Indicates the service name in the SDP record.
        uuid - Indicates the UUID in the SDP record.
        Returns:
        Returns an insecure RFCOMM SppServerSocket.
        Throws:
        IOException - Throws this exception if an error occurs, for example, Bluetooth is disabled or unavailable.
        Since:
        7

      • dataListenRfcomm

        public SppServerSocket dataListenRfcomm​(String name,
                                        UUID uuid)
                                 throws IOException
        Creates a secure RFCOMM Bluetooth server listening socket based on the service record.

        A remote device connecting to this socket is authenticated and communication over this socket is encrypted.

        Use SppServerSocket#accept to retrieve incoming connections from devices.

        The system will assign an unused RFCOMM channel.

        The system registers a Service Discovery Protocol (SDP) record with the local SDP server, records the service name, and automatically assigns a channel. Remote Bluetooth devices can use the same UUID to query the SDP server and identify the channel to connect to. This SDP record will be removed if the socket is disabled or the application exits unexpectedly.

        Parameters:
        name - Indicates the service name in the SDP record.
        uuid - Indicates the UUID in the SDP record.
        Returns:
        Returns a secure RFCOMM SppServerSocket.
        Throws:
        IOException - Throws this exception if an error occurs, for example, Bluetooth is disabled or unavailable.
        Since:

      • buildInsecureRfcommDataSocket

        public SppClientSocket buildInsecureRfcommDataSocket​(BluetoothRemoteDevice device,
                                                     UUID uuid)
                                              throws IOException
        Creates an insecure RFCOMM Bluetooth client socket based on the service record.

        This connection mode does not require link key authentication and may encounter man-in-the-middle attacks. For Bluetooth 2.1 devices, the link will be forcibly encrypted. For devices using earlier Bluetooth versions, the link will not be encrypted. If you need an encrypted communication channel, use buildRfcommDataSocket(ohos.bluetooth.BluetoothRemoteDevice, java.util.UUID).

        Use SppClientSocket#connect to initiate the outgoing connection.

        The system will assign an unused RFCOMM channel.

        Parameters:
        device - Indicates an bluetooth remote device.
        uuid - Indicates the UUID in the SDP record.
        Returns:
        Returns an insecure RFCOMM SppClientSocket.
        Throws:
        IOException - Throws this exception if an error occurs, for example, Bluetooth is disabled or unavailable.
        Since:
        7
